l name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Schaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: occupational name for a herdsman, from Middle High German <i>schāf</i>, <i>schāp</i> ‘sheep’."],"variants":[{"name":"Schaaf","meanings":["German: variant of   Schaf  .","Dutch: metonymic occupational name for a carpenter, from <i>schaaf</i> ‘plane’. Compare   Vanderschaaf   2."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de la Schaw was born in 1250, in Stirlingshire, Scotland, his father, John de la Schaw,, was 25 and his mother, Okand, was 25. He married Margaret. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1296, in Greenock, Inverclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1250–1296":"1250–1296","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1275–1323":"1275–1323","1225–1309":"1225–1309","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1225":"1225","1323":"1323","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1309":"1309","Scotland":"Scotland","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Greenock, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Greenock, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Greenock, Inverclyde, Renfrew, Scotland":"Greenock, Inverclyde, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–1296":"1250–1296","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1275–1323":"1275–1323","1225–1309":"1225–1309","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1225":"1225","1323":"1323","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1309":"1309","Scotland":"Scotl